ghteenth century. The close examination of these two important translations enable the formulation of not only a theory of creative vs. preservative translation but also the interconnections between literary theory and translation theory. Beebee also looks at later translations of Clarissa as products of literary and historical change and at Prévostian strategies of the novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aEnglish fictionxAppreciationzEurope. 0aEpistolary fiction, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aRape victims in literature. 0aSeduction in literature. 0aTranslating and interpretingxHistoryy18th century. 0aTranslating and interpretingxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen and literaturexHistoryy18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Reference.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271073316zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271073316423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271073316.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK